sentence: And uh, I did saw someone climbing up    uh, uh I guess it was a sheet, to try to get off of  something, trying to get  uh, uh, up on the roof.
zero-poss: No noun–noun possessive or nonstandard possessive pronoun appears; there is no clear possessive relationship in the clause.
zero-copula: Copula is overt where relevant (e.g., 'it was a sheet'); no missing BE before predicate or V‑ing.
double-tense: Although 'did saw' shows tense stacking across auxiliary and verb, the rule targets duplicated past morphology within a single word, which is not present.
be-construction: No uninflected finite 'be' with habitual/generic meaning occurs; only 'was' appears.
resultant-done: There is no preverbal 'done' marking completive aspect.
come: No stance/evaluative 'come' is used; 'come' does not appear at all.
double-modal: There is no sequence of two modals (e.g., 'might could') in a single verb chain.
multiple-neg: No negative elements occur, so negative concord is absent.
neg-inversion: No clause-initial negative auxiliary before the subject is present.
n-inv-neg-concord: There is no clause with both a negative subject and a negative verb; no negation at all occurs.
zero-3sg-pres-s: No 3sg present-tense verb without -s; 'it was' is past, and other verbs are nonfinite ('climbing', 'to get', 'trying').
is-was-gen: 'It was a sheet' has standard agreement (3sg + was); no generalized 'is/was' with non-matching subjects.
zero-pl-s: No clearly plural noun lacking plural -s occurs.
double-object: No personal dative pattern like 'I got me a X'; there is no subject–coreferential object pronoun + NP sequence.
wh-qu1: There is no WH-question (e.g., 'what', 'where') with missing DO or copula.
wh-qu2: No WH-question or embedded WH-clause appears, so no nonstandard WH word order.

demonstrative-them: No 'them' used as a determiner before a noun.
appositive-pleonastic-pronoun: No NP is followed by a co-referential pronoun in the same grammatical role.

zero-rel-pronoun: There is no subject relative clause modifying a noun without an overt relative pronoun.
preterite-had: No 'had' + verb used to express simple past appears.
bare-got: No present-possessive 'got' without 'have' occurs; only infinitival 'get' appears ('to get', 'trying to get').
